Bioethics emerged as a distinct interdisciplinary field in the mid-20th century, driven by rapid biomedical advances, historical atrocities (e.g., Nazi experiments, Tuskegee Syphilis Study), and societal demands for ethical oversight in research and clinical practice. A true quantitative meta-analysis is ill-suited to much of bioethics due to its normative, philosophical, and context-dependent character. Instead, scholars conduct systematic reviews or meta-reviews of empirical bioethics literature, argument-based reviews, and methodological syntheses.

