3. Core Framework: Principlism – Strengths, Critiques, and Adaptations
Strengths:
Practical, accessible mid-level principles bridging theory and practice.
Flexible via specification (refining principles for context) and balancing (weighing conflicts with justification).
Widespread use in guidelines, education, and policy. 

bioethics.pitt.edu

Major Critiques (from systematic and philosophical reviews):
Lack of hierarchy or clear arbitration: Principles can conflict (e.g., autonomy vs. beneficence in paternalism cases) without a systematic resolution method beyond ad hoc balancing. Critics like Clouser and Gert argue they are inconsistent because drawn from rival theories (Kantian, utilitarian, etc.). 

pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov +1

Theoretical thinness: Accused of being "the Borg of bioethics" (assimilating without depth) or culturally biased toward Western individualism (over-emphasizing autonomy). 

journals.library.columbia.edu

Insufficient for emerging issues: Limited for relational ethics, virtue ethics, care ethics, or global challenges like climate-health intersections and AI.
Empirical grounding: Some studies show principles do not always predict real-world decisions consistently. 

blogs.biomedcentral.com

Alternatives and Hybrids:
Virtue ethics, casuistry (case-based), narrative ethics, feminist/care ethics.
Capability approaches, responsible innovation frameworks for technology. 

link.springer.com

Proposals to elevate compassion or other principles for arbitration. 

link.springer.com

European emphases on dignity, solidarity, and human rights alongside or instead of the "Georgetown mantra." 

